1. Backgound

Beyond being a mere means of communication, the language system of a community is also a carrier of collective thought. This position is all the more reinforced when it comes to thoughts on sensitive issues directly linked to morals and culture, such as births, marriages and deaths. As such, understanding sensitive issues pertaining to births, marriages and deaths registration could be achieved through careful study of language use.

This study is part of a research project to study the knowledge, social norms and cultural practices associated with the registration of births, marriages and deaths in Burkina Faso. One question that comes to mind is: Is it possible to utilize text mining, Natural Language Processing (NLP), machine learning and other data science methods to shed insight on such a topic?

As an exploratory analysis, this R markdown document will attempt to get an overview of some of the key issues discussed by publications on Birth, Marriage and Death registration in Burkina Faso. It is designed to supply our study on the proximate determinants of under-registration of vital events in Burkina Faso with a flow of information to better prepare for field interviews/focus group and guide the analyses. It also aims to advocate for further studies on the social norms that determine vital events registration while encouraging the use of a new method of data collection in this type of study.

2. Text Mining

Text mining is a text analytics process that aims to discover relevant information that is possibly unknown or buried beneath words. Natural Language Processing (NLP) is one text mining methodology. It tries to decipher the ambiguities in written language by tokenization, clustering, extracting entity and word relationships, and using algorithms to identify themes and quantify subjective information (Liske, 2018). For this study we will try to decipher from our analytics the popular thought about civil registration in Burkina Faso, focusing on aspects related to socio-cultural norms and gender.

2.2. Loading the dataset

We hypothesize that publications are a major source of information for understanding public opinion on topical issues such as civil registration. This is also the reason why this study was not limited to academic publications, which are almost non-existent. Our dataset has been conceived based on a desk review of different types of publications on Birth, Marriage and Death registration in Burkina Faso. In some cases, we have gone beyond texts that simply discuss vital events registration to consider texts that examine the socio-cultural norms around these events as that is what interests us most. This is the case, for example, of marriages where we found some academic publications on their processes, forms, and the place they occupy in Burkinabe society. Our database has 6 columns, namely the number assigned to each publication (Num), the year of publication (Year), the type of publication (Publication_Type), whether its source is national or not (Source_Type), the type of vital event it discusses (Vital_Event), the text of the publication (Text) and its source (Source). All included publications were collected through google/google scholar searches, using different keywords.

unstructured_BMD <- read_excel("/Users/ramoudaneorousannou/unfpa_bf/Unstructured_Birth_Marriage_Death_Reg_Bf.xlsx")

In total, between 2004 and 2019 we obtained 33 publications on the theme that are available online. There are certainly publications on birth, marriage and death registration in Burkina Faso that have been missed, especially those that are not on the web. Weve got 19 publications on birth registration, 13 on mariage and only 1 on Death registration. This result already suggests that death registration is currently not a topical issue in Burkina Faso.

2.4. Publications types

Publication_Types_by_Year <- unstructured_BMD %>%

count()
Publication_Types_by_Year

One striking result is that the social norms that influence vital events registration in Burkina Faso are hardly addressed in the academic literature. Only 4 academic documents that we could find discussed the issue. However, some academic documents may be available in hard copy, offline. Most of the publications used in this R markdown come from online newspapers, in particular Le Faso.net which has extensively discussed the subject and from Jeune Afrique. Other online newspapers such as Fasozine.com, lepays.bf, touteinfo.com, fasoamazone.net have been scrutinized using french keywords such as naissance, mariage, dcs.

To facilitate the text mining process and given that Burkina Faso is a French-speaking country, we limited our search to texts written in French.

The publications we found were from 2004 to 2019 and the majority of them focus on birth registration, with 2010 and 2018 having the highest number of publications. Note that most of the publications in the early years focus on birth registration, indicating that the issue has been topical for more than 15 years (because the advent of internet in Burkina Faso is likely to be recent). The same applies to marriages. Conversely, deaths registration is rarely discussed and the only publication found in the news was from 2010.

# Get rid of apostrophes and perform some manual stemmatization by creating a little function that handles most scenarios using gsub(), and then apply that function across all words
fix_apostrophe <- function(w) {
  # I am using "w" to mean "word"
  w <- gsub("l'enregistrement", "enregistrement", w)
  w <- gsub("lenregistrement", "enregistrement", w)
  w <- gsub("denregistrement", "enregistrement", w)
  w <- gsub("lenregistrement", "enregistrement", w)
  w <- gsub("l'importance", "importance", w)
  w <- gsub("limportance", "importance", w)
  w <- gsub("l'hpital", "hpital", w)
  w <- gsub("lhpital", "hpital", w)
  w <- gsub("l'unicef", "unicef", w)
  w <- gsub("d'actes", "actes", w)
  W <- gsub("dactes", "actes", w)
  w <- gsub("lacte", "acte", w)
  w <- gsub("lunion", "union", w)
  w <- gsub("cest", "est", w)
  w <- gsub("ltat", "tat", w)
  w <- gsub("l'tat", "tat", w)
  w <- gsub("dtat", "tat", w)
  w <- gsub("d'tat", "tat", w)
  w <- gsub("dun", "un", w)
  w <- gsub("leglise", "eglise", w)
  w <- gsub("lopration", "opration", w)
  w <- gsub("lenfant", "enfant", w)
  w <- gsub("lunicef", "unicef", w)
  w <- gsub("dautres", "autres", w)
  w <- gsub("hommes", "homme", w)
  w <- gsub("femmes", "femme", w)
  w <- gsub("couples", "couple", w)
  w <- gsub("filles", "femme", w)
  w <- gsub("dinstruction", "instruction", w)
  w <- gsub("lage" , "age", w)
  w <- gsub("droits", "droit", w)
  w <- gsub("maternits", "materni", w)
  w <- gsub("centres", "centre", w)
  w <- gsub("maire", "mairie", w)
  w <- gsub("familles", "famille", w)
  return(w)
}

In addition, a word that appears only four times but refers to a cultural practice related to marriage is "levirat.levirat" refers to the obligation of the real or classificatory brother of a deceased man to marry his widow or widows. It is a widespread practice in West Africa, although it has various conditions for its implementation: it can be imposed, prescribed, recommended or left to the widows choice (Attan, 2014).

2.7.2. Insight: Birth registration

Based on this plot, we could notice that the word enregistrement (registration) came out strongly from publications on birth. This is normal as the publications were on birth registration. However, this also tells us that birth Registration in Burkina Faso is often viewed as a simple registration act and not necessarily as a social act. There are also words like droit (right), gouvernement (government), that reveal governmental strong implication in getting all births counted in Burkina Faso. The presence of icivil, which is a newly introduced birth registration technology via mobile phone, indicates a strong inclination to modernize the system, notwithstanding limiting factors such as the accessibility and availability of the technology in province or region which are also words that have appeared.

2.7.3. Insight : Death registration

It is difficult to make sense of the graph on death registration because there was only one publication on this subject. Nevertheless, this suggests that little is being done to register deaths and that it would be important for our study to shed light on the reasons for this situation.

2.7.4. Insight: Marriage registration

For publications on marriages, the word femme appears more frequently and reflects the central role that women play on this issue. We also notice the frequent use of the word scolarises (educated) and instruction. Here, the presence of the es at the end of the word indicates that it is used as a verb for a female pronoun, therefore it refers to womens education. We can infer that womens education is linked to their marriage and ultimately to the registration of marriages.

A word that appeared with a relatively high frequency and that seemed a priori meaningless to us is pug. After a review of some texts on marriage, we realized that pug is the stem of several words in the local language such as pug-siure (engagement ceremony), pug-pusum (marriage proposal to a womans family). Pug means woman in the local dialect and therefore reinforces the argument that women are at the center of the debates on marriage registration.

Additionally, we see words such as choix (choice), union, libre(free), fuite (flee) that are used to talk about the types of marriage and also about the possibility of having a divorce. It is therefore possible that the registration of marriages depends on the type of union and the fear that the woman will flee.

3. Topic Modeling

Topic modeling allows us to move beyond simple word counts and uncover the underlying topics in our collection of documents (in this case, our transformed publications). We will use a standard topic model known as Lattent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA). The LDA model is a type of unsupervised learning approach that seaches for patterns of words consitently occuring together accross a collection of documents. Before runing our topic model, we need to transform the collection of words (token_BMD3) into a collection of documents called Document Term Matrix (DTM). A DTM is a matrix that has a single row for each document (publication) and a column for every unique word (or term). The values in the DTM are the counts of each term for a given document in a row.

3.1. Topic modeling for birth registration

dtm_publications_birth <- token_BMD3 %>%
rename(id = Num) %>% # to rename the num column 
filter(Vital_Event == "Birth") %>%
count(word, id) %>%
cast_dtm(id, word, n)

arrange(desc(beta))

We defined k = 2 because we want the model to group the words into two topics. The result shows us beta which is the probability of words appearing in a given topic.

# Creating an object for words' probabilities of appearance

word_prob_birth <- lda_publications_birth_topics %>%
group_by(topic) %>%
top_n(20, beta) %>%
ungroup() %>%
mutate(term2 = fct_reorder(term, beta))

# Ploting words' propabilities

ggplot(word_prob_birth, aes(term2, beta, 
                      fill = as.factor(topic))) +
  geom_col() +
  facet_wrap(~ topic, scales = "free") +
  coord_flip() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1)) +
labs(#title = paste("Topic Modeling for Birth Registration in Burkina Faso"),
     x = "Terms",
     y = "Probability of apperance",
  fill = "Topics")

The first topic have words like enregistrement, icivil, politique, national, etat appearing together with a high probability and therefore suggests that the topic is related to the introduction of icivil as a national birth registration system in Burkina Faso.

The second topic is a collection of words that seem to be related to the modernization of birth registration and the challenges associated with it. With words like enregistrement (registration), modernisation, province, region, we can deduce the need to go to remote areas and therefore the distance factor in birth registration. Still in this quest for modernization, we see words like programme, operation, millions occuring together with a higher probability indicating that there are several ad hoc birth registration programmes and suggesting the possible absence of an effective sustainable system.

# Ploting words' propabilities

ggplot(word_prob_marriage, aes(term2, beta, fill = as.factor(topic))) +
  geom_col() +
  facet_wrap(~ topic, scales = "free") +
  coord_flip() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1)) +
labs(#title = paste("Topic Modeling for Marriage Registration in Burkina Faso"),
     x = "Terms",
     y = "Probability of apperance",
  fill = "Topics")

The first topic that has a collection of words appearing together with a high probability as mairie (town hall), couple, maris (married) is possibly on the celebration of civil marriage and therefore its registration. The marked presence of the word collectif is certainly an allusion to the celebration of collective civil marriages which happens to be a quite interesting phenomenon in Burkina Faso. Indeed, these are civil marriage ceremonies organized for several people at a time, by the same registrar, on the same day. This method appears here as a means of encouraging the registration of marriages. Thus, one question that comes to the mind is whether seeing ones friend or relative perform a civil marriage can be a determining factor in the registration of a given individuals marriage in Burkina Faso.

The second topic probably concerns the social factors that affect marriage. We see words like:

  • jeune (young) so age as a factor,

  • niveau (level of education), scolarises (enrolled in school),scolarisation (school enrolment), instruction (education), therefore education as another factor,

  • family, so the environment as a factor

  • pug, which is a word in local dialect that means woman but refers mainly to traditional marriage systems (tradition here as a factor),

  • choix (choice),libre (free), as types of union and processus (process) referring to the duration of a union,

  • fuite (flee) which refers to separation and therefore the probability of divorce as a factor.

The interpretation of a topic model is quite subjective but already allows - with a certain mastery of the subject - to make certain predictions about the words that indicate a determinant of the registration of a vital event such as marriage.

The absence of a large number of publications on social norms does not allow conclusions to be drawn and some of the determinants to be predicted. For example, although we have obtained several texts on birth registration, very few deal with the socio-cultural barriers or norms that may hinder their registration. On the other hand, on marriage, we have reached more interesting conclusions, with fewer texts but oriented towards the social determinants that interest us. The results we have here can, in combination with the data that will be collected during field studies, confirm or refute some of our assumptions.

Ideally, we should be able to repeat this analysis with the transcripts from the interviews and focus groups and consolidate our interpretations based on the information gathered in the field.
